compass the conflicting energies of the age. In the idea of vocation she found a way to explore how far it is possible to be ambitious both for oneself and for a large cause, and a way to probe the contradictions between ambitious, self-defining work and the older institutions; of family, community, and religion. The book is solidly grounded in cultural and historical reality. Although Mintz concentrate on George Eliot and especially Middlemarch, he also examines the conceptions of self and work in Victorian biographies and autobiographies and the emergence in late-nineteenth-century fiction of the idea of the vocation of art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEnglische Literatur. 0aLiterature. 0aVocation dans la littérature. 0aVocation in literature. 0aVocation. 4aEliot, George, 1819-1880 Middlemarch. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors. 4aVocation in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Literature eBook Packagez9783110353501oZDB-23-HLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067442855340uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067442856040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674428560423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674428560/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-HCO  aZDB-23-HLI